76561198063959748,Recommended,220660,13811617,"Posted: 3 January, 2015",all,IronBeagle,"Having no idea of what the game was ""supposed"" to be, I simply bought the game expecting a fancier ""MOO2"" so to speak.    And given the negative reviews I kept reading about it, I lowered my expectations greatly and bought the game on massive sale.Once I actually played the game, I actually wound up enjoying it quite a bit.   I can't recall how many hours I've spent and how many ""races"" I've created in trying the game.  I'll try to rate the game on a 5-star system on each of the areas that I can think of:1.) Graphics - 4/5- I truly enjoyed the graphics.  I really did.  Being able to zoom in to my ships, the combat animations, the effects of each weapon being unique in their own right.  I especially like the unique ship designs for each race which attempted to match their species.  A little cliched, but then again, what game isn't nowadays?2.) UI - 3/5- Simple enough and inuitive.  A few grips would be on some screens where it seems like the UI was designed with a different resolution in mind.  I have an old monitor only capable of 1280 x 1024 and it stuggles on the setup screen due to odd text wrapping.  Other than that however, I felt the UI easy enough to navigate.3.) Gameplay - 3.5/5- I found myself in several sleepless nights playing that ""one more turn"" (or in this case, one more minute given it's real time).  The racial creation allows for varied types of empires to play around with and with each game randomizing the different empires behavior, it's always been a treat for me.  However, there is one glaring bug around the ""plot"" where if the AI winds up wiping out the triggers, you're SoL if that was your main goal for that particular round of gameplay.  I've actually had to go in to the XML save files to try to re-trigger the events which is never a good sign.  Still, that plot isn't the end-all-be-all of the game and isn't a deal-breaker for me.- Another nice twist is the actual race creator.  Unlike a true ""creator"", you simply overwrite a species for the current game.  However, any designs you create while playing that ""race"" become available to the AI in succeeding games so you eventually wind up fighting your own designs which was a real treat when I saw it happen.- Related to gamelay, there are a few things which could have been improved on in my opinion.   Tech Tree, for one, is smaller compared to other 4X games.  It only feels large due to the amount of research points needed to unlock higher tiers.  The AI also sometimes behaves oddly despite their racial setting at game time (i.e. an Honorable AI will sometimes keep stealing from you despite being in an non-agression pact).4.)  Replayability - 3/5- I admit I keep replaying the game.  For me, it's been enjoyable.  However, I do see 2 problems which can hinder it in other cases:a) Memory optimization: unlike other RTS games (which this game has flavors of), there is no unit cap other than your bank account (i.e. turn-by-turn income).  This is both a blessing and curse.  This means that you can build up quite the fleet and swarm your way through the galaxy.  Unfortunately this also means unless you've got godly amounts of RAM (and I'm talking 16+ GB of RAM), your game can quickly grind to a halt and crash as the AI will spam ships like no tomorrow.   Even the ""final plot story"" can break your game should you unlock it given that it also spams ships like no tomorrow (without the limitation of a factory's output to slow it down).  Related to this, beware of designing ""cheap"" gunboats.  As the race creator ""overwrites"" a species, any design you create becomes available to that AI race and it tends to favor spamming those cheap gunboats.b) No multiplayer.  I never expected this feature as I never was an early backer.  I can see how this would put off others as the challenge of beating down your frenemies always extends the life of a game.  The lack of this feature can put off many people from getting the game.c) Lack of a real ""custom"" race.  MOO2 had the same issues but it would have been nice to have a custom race that didn't overwrite existing ones.5.) Overall - 3/5- I liked MOO3.  Yes, I said it.  I actually came to like game.  StarDrive feels like what MOO3 tried to be.  4X strategy with RTS gameplay.  StarDrive for me is an enjoyable single-player 4X game which allows for some small to medium scale games.  Large games are completely out of the question due to the memory problem which would have raised the game to 4/5 or me.  If you ignore what was originally promised and take the game for what it is now, it's actually worth a try.I would purchase it when it's at least 50% off given the isssues and replayability challenges it may give others.For the current price of $32.99 CDN, I would instead spend it on Space Empires V or Pandora as they have a bit more replayability for most in my opinion."
