76561197978782798,Recommended,220660,8984891,"Posted: 5 February, 2014",all,Corvus Dove,"While this is a great game worth a look, a ball was dropped somewhere that makes you feel like you bought half a game.    You can assume manual control over your ""flagship"" but this is sort of useless; I find myself never making use of the ability.  That, coupled with the fact that there's a game type selector but no game type except the default, tells me that this game started with the intent to develop something akin to StarFlight or Star Control II, but that inability to manage scope led it to becoming just another Sins of a Solar Empire clone.That said, the AI is challenging, though it tends to make odd choices at times.   Unfortunately, the races are very predictable in behavior, and seem a bit like ripoffs themselves.   The Kulrathi warrior bear race reminds me a little much of the Kilrathi warrior cat race from old Wing Commander.   There's a race of squid-beings that have ships and philosophy very similar to the Reapers from Mass Effect.I did enjoy playing this game for one or two playthroughs, and the modification of the ships is an interesting mechanic, but I found myself going back to Sins of a Solar Empire to get this sort of fix.   Between the lack of creativity on the alien races and the clear false-start of creating an ""adventure"" mode, I was never able to shake the feeling that the game was completed halfway and the rest was just phoned in.   It's a game worth playing if you can grab it on Steam Sale, but it's also a lesson in how scope creep can turn a great idea into an unfinished project."
